First Generation

1.1* John French, b. 1759 in Cornwall, England, m. Joan Kellow on 10 Apr 1787 in Tintagel, Cornwall, England, d. 28 Oct 1826 in Tintagel, Cornwall, England at age 67. Residence Trevena, same as Tintagel.

Tintagel or Trevena is a civil parish and village situated on the Atlantic coast of Cornwall, England. The village and nearby Tintagel Castle (see photo below) are associated with the legends surrounding King Arthur and in recent times has become a tourist attraction.

Joan Kellow, was the daughter of William Kellow (1736-1813) and Catherine Bishop (1738-1813). She was christened on 13 Jan 1767 in Tintagel, Cornwall, England, and died on 31 Dec 1836 in Tintagel, Cornwall, England [7]. She was buried 20 Jan 1826 at St.  Endellion Church, residence Scarrabine, age 60. The Kellow family is documented back to about 1600 in Cornwall, England. The French family is documented only back to John French, b. 1759. Only 2 of their 9 children immigrated to Canada. See [12] for details.  

To make an educated guess as to who was John French’s father, an assumption could be made that he lived in Tintagel, Cornwall, England around 1759 when John was born. Only these children are listed and were born about that time and in that same place, but without any positive relationship to John. Their father Henry French could have been John’s father or uncle. Reviewing the birthdates, another child was born in the same year as John.

Philippe French (dau), b. 1753, baptized 28 Mar 1753 in Trevalga, her parents were Henry and Philippe French
Abel French, b. 1755, baptized 18 Jan 1755 in Forrabury, his parents were Henry and Philippe French
Henry French, b. 1759, baptized 1 Jul 1759 in Trevalga, his parents were Henry and Philippe French
Thomas French, b. 1760, baptized 13 Jun 1760 in Forrabury, his parents were Henry and Philippe French
Susannah French, b. 1763, baptized 23 May 1763 in Trevalga, her parents were Henry and Philippe French
Samuel French, b. 1765, baptized 10 Mar 1765 in Forrabury, his parents were Henry and Philippe French
Moses French, b. 1767, baptized 16 Mar 1767 in Forrabury, his parents were Henry and Philippe French


John’s father may have been Henry French who married Philippe. Henry would have been born 1733 or before. Listed is a Henry French, born 1729, died 2 Jul 1794 in Forrabury. The website www.findmypast.co.uk shows no other clear connection. Henry French married Philippa Tucker (or Tooker) on 27 Feb 1749. This marriage date fits in with the birthdates of the children listed above, but no authentic connection has been determined to John French.

Second Generation, the Immigrant Sons of John French

Children of John French and Joan Kellow, 1.1

Two of John and Joan’s children immigrated to Canada. Their other children did not immigrate to Canada (showing children’s birthdates): Jane 1787; Elizabeth 1789; Mary Ann 1791; Francis 1791; John 1794; [Thomas 1800 immigrated]; Ann 1802; [James 1803 immigrated]; Abel 1809.

John French’s two sons immigrated from Cornwall, England (shown by red marker) to Prince Edward Island, labeled PE on this map. Prince Edward Island is Canada’s smallest province located on the east coast of North America.

2.1* Thomas French, b. 1800, Tintagel, Cornwall, England, baptized 17 Jun 1800 in Tintagel, the son of John and Joan French. He married Mary Hume Kellow on 6 Feb 1834 in PEI, daughter of James Kellow and Janie Tippett. Mary was born 25 Apr 1810 in Padstow, Cornwall, England, and died May 27, 1903 in Westmoreland, Lot 29, PEI. Thomas was a farmer and a Methodist [6]. Thomas d. before 1891, Westmoreland, Lot 29, Prince Edward Island (PEI) [6]. For details, see [22].

 

2.2* James Richard French, b. 20 Dec 1803 in Tintagel, Cornwall, England, christened 20 Dec 1803 in Tintagel, Cornwall, England. He m. 18 Aug 1829 [6] in St. Peter’s Church, Liverpool, England to Jemima “Jenny” Lloyd [1] [7]. She was b. 23 Dec 1803 at Caernarvanshire (Powys or Porthlwyd), N. Wales, per her gravestone, the daughter of Richard Lloyd (d. 1845) of Porth Lloyd and Elizabeth Williams Lloyd (d. after 1850). Jemima died on 28 Dec 1878 in Detroit, Wayne, Michigan, USA. See [13] for details.  

James immigrated to Prince Edward Island, Canada in about 1830 with his wife Jemima Lloyd with whom he eloped. In 1850 James at age 47 left on a sea voyage from Canada and was never heard from thereafter. The ship was lost. Further notation suggests he died presumably in the waters of Indonesia [7] [1] [3]. See [14] and [15] for details.

Captain French was a founding member of the town of Victoria (from the area called Westmoreland) along with brother Thomas. Victoria, tucked neatly on the south shore of Prince Edward Island, halfway between PEI’s largest cities of Charlottetown and Summerside, was founded in 1819 by James Bardin Palmer, an immigrant lawyer and agent for the Earl of Westmoreland. James French had arrived in Westmoreland about 10 years after James Palmer. Today (2021) Victoria has less than 100 inhabitants and Westmoreland has even fewer.

For the 70 years after James’ immigration, the French family descendants were the carpenters, boat builders, wheelwrights, home builders and church builders in the area. James was also active as a whaler in the North Atlantic, and a farmer. Captain James’ daughter-in-law, Barbara Holm, apparently mentioned to a cousin, that he was a pirate.

3.13* Richard Lloyd French [3], b. 9 Mar 1841, Lot 29, PEI, bapt. 29 Aug 1841, at Hampton United Church, Prince Edward Island, Canada [6] [8], d. 13 Dec 1889 at sea and is buried in the Arlington National Cemetery, Arlington, VA outside WDC. Age 48 years, 9 months, 4 days [8]. Remains removed from Oak Hill Cemetery to Arlington National Cemetery on March 27, 1928.

He may have changed his name to “Ricardo Ddelweddo French” to honor his Welsh heritage [8]. He was a medical doctor in the District of Columbia whose medical library and surgical instruments were sold by his wife in March 1891.

The Washington Post
Saturday, December 14, 1889
Died
French. On Friday, December 13, 1889, Dr. R.D. DeL. French, aged forty-eight years. Funeral from his late residence, 1316 T Street Northwest, on Monday, December 16, at 2 o’clock PM. Friends of the family are invited to attend. See [17] and [20] for details.

His first wife was Irene Sophronia Marlow, whom he married on 10 Feb 1872 in WDC. Another record states he married Irene S. Marlow on 8 Feb 1877 in WDC. She was b. 1 Jul 1846 in WDC, d. 24 Mar 1928 in Drummond, Montgomery, MD, buried at the Arlington National Cemetery outside WDC. From the 1880 Census of WDC, it is reported that Richard changed the spelling of his surname to the phonetic pronunciation to honor Spanish and Welsh origins [8].

Irene Marlow is listed in the 1870 census as living in WDC with the Robinson family, her sister Sue L. Marlow, and 3 others with different surnames. Her death record shows her name as Irene Marlow French, age 81, died 3 Mar 1928 in WDC, the daughter of John H. Marlow and Maryann Welmore, and that she married Ricardo D. Dle. French on 10 Feb 1872. They had daughters Irene E. G. French and Brenta L. M. French (1875 in WDC), where this French family ends.

They had 2 daughters Irene El Alma French Wallace, 1873-1942. See [21] for details.

Obituary

Richard D. French, 89, died at Provincial House Wednesday evening.

He was born June 7, 1890, in Detroit where he was raised and educated. He served with the Marines at age 14 as a drummer boy from 1905-1911 in Panama and Nicaragua. He then graduated from Detroit Eastern High School. He attended Detroit University where he studied architecture.

He entered real estate business, first working for Albert Kahn, Detroit architect, and later started his own business. He was president of the United Builders Association of Detroit in 1923. 

He married the former Miss Jean Rennie July 26, 1930, in Ohio. Mr. French later moved to Bay City where he owned and operated the R.D. French Ford dealership until his retirement in 1950. He was a pioneer in the pratice of furnishing driver training cars to area high schools. 

He served in Bay City as Third Ward councilman in 1956, and was an elder in the First Presbyterian Church of Bay City. He was both rifle and pistol champion of Michigan in 1931 and an officer with 125th Infantry of the Michigan National Guard.

He was a charter member of the East Side Detroit Lion's Club, Bay City Rotary Club, Bay City Elks, Veterans of Foreign Wars, Bay City Commandry, Royal Arch Masons and Knights Templar and Joppa Lodge of Bay City. Mr. French moved to Midland in 1973 and was a member of the First United Methodist Church.

He leaves his wife Jean; a son, Richard D. French of Detroit; a daughter Mrs. Charles (Lillian) Poole of Midland; and four grandchildren.

Services will be at 11 a.m. Saturday in the Fires United Methodist Church with the Revs. John Parrish and Ira Bush officiating. Burial will be in Midland cemetery. 
A Masonic memorial service will be conducted in the Wilson funeral home at 8 p.m. Friday. Friends may call any time. Midland Daily News

Notes

Another French family immigrated from Cornwall, Otterham Mill Parish, England. These children were born between 1784 and 1807 and immigrated to Prince Edward Island: Elizabeth, William, Alice, Thomas, Grace, Abel, Tamasins. This information came from Mrs. Aubrey French of Cookshire, Quebec in 1986.

Another French family immigrated from Cornwall to Compton Co., Quebec, Canada. William French who m. Elizabeth McGee in 1857 in Massachusetts had 8 children born between 1862 and 1875: James, William, Robert, Henry, Margery, Mary, Margaret, Lizzie.

[10] The “Passenger and Immigration Lists Index” on ancestry.com shows George French in 1747 in Maryland, from data derived from return-forms connected with the naturalization of “Foreign Protestants”, papers that were sent from the Colonies to the Lords’ Commissioners for Trade and Plantations. The “Foreign Protestants” were a group of immigrants to Nova Scotia in the mid-18th century and the ethnonymical basis behind the name “New Brunswick”, as well as support behind naming "Prince Edward Island" for a representative of the Braunschweiger dynasty. At that time, Nova Scotia was a British colony, but populated by 10,000 French-speaking and Roman Catholic Acadians which was a great problem by the British administrators of the area. Attracting British immigrants was difficult as most preferred to go the warmer southern colonies. Therefore, a plan was developed to aggressively recruit “Foreign Protestants”. These came mostly from German duchies and principalities on the Upper Rhine Palatinate area, and the duchy of Württemberg was the major source, but there were also “Foreign Protestants” from Monbéliard in France (very close to the German border), and parts of Switzerland and the Netherlands. The British government agreed to provide free passage to the colony, as well as free land and one year’s rations upon arrival. These new arrivals spoke German, except those from Switzerland and Monbéliard who spoke French. But, . . . these were mostly from 1749 and the French family’s earliest known whereabouts was in 1747, two years prior.

[23] Century of Immigration, Marriage and Death Records, 1780-1900, by Leland Currie. Century of Immigration, Marriage and Death Records is a book of transcriptions on CD in .pdf format for Mac and PCs. It contains transcriptions of marriage announcements, death notices, obituaries, inquest reports, and news items from Prince Edward Island Newspapers for over a century from 1780-1900. These records were transcribed from nearly the entire P.E.I. newspapers on microfilm at the National Archives of Canada.

The CD is set up like a book with a Table of Contents, Search Tips, Chapters by decades for Marriages, Deaths and Immigration. The CD contains over 2,200 pages of searchable records. Each entry is source referenced for newspaper and date and contains over 90,000 source citations from over 50 newspapers during that century.

The CD is professionally produced and doesn't require any special app other than a .pdf reader such as the free Adobe Reader or Foxit PDF Reader. The collection took over 5 years to collect and transcribe and is an invaluable reference for family history research. Website: http://www.islandregister.com/century%20of%20immigration.html.

Contact Lee Currie at ballantynetrail@live.ca for current pricing and for ordering.

Hello:

My name is Shirley MacKinnon and I am tracing my grandfather, James Ramsay's family history.  He is Arthur Ramsay's brother.

Gertrude French and Arthur Ramsay had the following children:

Harold Ramsay, born: Sept. 15, 1900

Mable Ramsay born:  Sept. 1904

Addie M. Ramsay April 1908

Source:  1911 PEI Census

I believed they moved to Boston, Mass. area.  I remember my Mom talking about Mable coming home for visits from Boston, Mass.  She married a Mr. Manning who worked as a lineman for the telephone co.

I checked the web for Harold Ramsay 1900 and found one deceased in 1972 in Bridgewater, Plymouth, Massachusetts.  Could not find his obtituary.

My grandfather, James Ramsay worked in Boston where he met my grandmother Mary Blue MacDonald also from PEI.  She was nursing in Boston at that time.  They moved back to PEI.

I will read your family history for any clues to help me find my grandfather or his parents.  His parents are unknown at this time.

Shirley
